\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284 Midnight came and went. The summer solstice should be celebrated at dawn. That's what Fargo had said. And he took the celebration seriously, so where was he?\par
Jeff finally slept, uneasily, because he was worried and because he could hear Norby exploring the apartment, opening books and fiddling with equipment-and he couldn't help won\-dering if Norby were doing any damage.\par
But mostly he was worried about Fargo. Fargo was a good brother. He'd been almost like a parent, reliable and respon\-sible, except for his habit of getting into trouble unintentionally and upsetting schedules.\par
"Wake up! It's almost dawn!"\par
"Fargo?" said Jeff, rubbing his eyes.\par
"It's Norby. If you want to celebrate the solstice at dawn in the park, you'd better go."\par
"But Fargo isn't here, and the park's not all that safe-"\par
Norby's head popped up to full extent. "Not safe! What are you worrying about? You have me, don't you? I'll protect you."\par
"You're too little. I need Fargo. He's an expert in martial arts. He's been teaching me, but I'm not as good as he is, and he made me promise I wouldn't go into the park at night without him."\par
"What are martial arts? Show me."\par
"All right," said Jeff, getting out of bed and shaking his head woozily, "if you'll let me wash up first."\par
Fifteen minutes later he was in his pants and shirt. He struck a pose in front of Norby and yelled.\par
"Well?" said Norby, after waiting a little. "What happens next?"\par
"You're supposed to attack me."\par
Norby promptly rushed at Jeff, who leaned back, grabbed one of Norby's arms in passing, and heaved.\par
The barrel hit the opposite wall and bounced to the floor. All the limbs had been reeled in and all the openings shut as soon as Jeff had let go. The barrel rolled across the room.\par
"Norby? Are you all right? I didn't mean to throw you so hard. It was just reflex."\par
No sound came from the barrel.\par
"Hey, are you damaged, Norby?"\par
The sound came, muffled and sulky, "I can't be damaged- physically. But my feelings are hurt."\par
"You're not supposed to have feelings."\par
"But I do, just the same. Just because you're human doesn't mean you have the right to decide I don't have feelings."\par
"I'm really sorry. I'll be more careful." Jeff picked up Norby and started toward the door. Norby's barrel was awkward and heavy, and Jeff realized he had a hard task on his hands.\par
Norby's hat elevated, and his eyes looked at Jeff. "What are you doing, Jeff?"\par
"I'm carrying you to the park. I thought maybe you wouldn't want to walk on those short legs."\par
"What you mean is that with your long legs it would be painful for you to shorten your stride to match mine, right?"\par
"Well, yes."\par
Norby made a small grinding noise. "You mean well, Jeff, but there's a great deal you don't know."\par
"I never denied that," said Jeff.\par
"And well you shouldn't. I'll let you in on a secret."\par
"What secret?"\par
"This one," said Norby, extruding a hand that grabbed Jeff's. He then floated upward and forward, pulling a surprised Jeff toward the window.\par
"You've got antigrav!" shouted Jeff. "Miniaturized anti-"\par
"Not so loud," said Norby. "We don't need to have everyone hear about it."\par
"Ouch!" said Jeff, his head grazing the bottom of the lifted windowpane. He had time to be glad that their apartment was so old that it had windows that could open, and then he was sailing across Fifth Avenue toward Central Park. He wasn't dangling downward with an arm being pulled out of its socket, as he would have been if he were holding onto a passive rope. Instead it was as though Norby's antigrav were spread out over him, holding him up, lifting him....\par
Norby said, "I \i thought I \i0 had antigrav, but you can never tell. I suppose I can remember how to work it."\par
Central Park was beneath them now. Behind them, low in the east, the sky showed a diffuse light behind the skyscrapers even though the sun was not yet up. Beneath them the park was still in the deep shadow of night.\par
"I've always wondered what personal antigrav would be like," said Jeff, excited and breathless. The wind whipped his curly brown hair back from his forehead.\par
"It's hard work, if you want to know, and I don't know when my next electric bath will come."\par
"It seems easy to me. Easy and delightful, like swim\-ming in an ocean of water you can't feel, like swooping through-"\par
"That's because you're not the one who's producing the antigrav field, so it's no work to you," grumbled Norby. "Don't get so stuck up about how it feels that you forget to hang on. Hold more tightly! Also, tell me where I'm supposed to go for this solstice celebration of yours."\par
"It's in the Ramble-that wooded section beyond the boat-house, with the boating pond circling 'round to the other side. Go down-now."\par
"Not so fast. I've got to figure out how. We can't just drop. You'll dent a bone or something. Besides, it's dark, and I can't make my internal light bright enough to show the ground with\-out running out of power. I can't do antigrav and bright light both. What do you think I am? A nuclear powerhouse?" Norby circled, and they sank downward, then up again with a jerk.\par
"Hey," shouted Jeff, "watch out!"\par
\i "\i0 Look\i , \i0 I've got to get this right, don't I?" said Norby. "It's not easy to ease into the gravitational field and let yourself sink just right." He grunted. "Okay-now-now. I wish I breathed so I could hold my breath."\par
"I'll hold mine," said Jeff.\par
"Good! That helps psychologically. It's hard to make out the ground from the shadow in this dark."\par
With a thump that rattled his teeth, Jeff found himself on his knees and elbows, which were dug well into moist dirt. His head stuck out over a pool of goldfish in the center of the small grassy clearing. They were lucky-it was the very place Jeff would have had Norby aim for if it had been light enough to see.\par
Jeff could see the goldfish despite the dark. The pool seemed to be lighted from within, which was odd, because Manhattan was usually too broke for fancy lighting in public parks.\par
"Norby! Where are you?" Jeff called, trying to shout in a whisper.\par
The light in the pool brightened, and slowly a shape rose up and out of the water. It was a barrel shape, draped in water lilies. It continued to rise until it was suspended a foot over the water, and then it spun rapidly in the air, scattering drops, as a dog shaking itself would do.\par
Jeff received some of the spray and shouted, "Hey!"\par
The barrel slowly stopped spinning. Two legs emerged from the bottom and started a good try at a dignified walk-in the air-down to Jeff.\par
Norby's hat popped up. "I didn't judge it quite right. I turned on illumination just a little too late. Still, that was an excellent landing, if I do say so myself."\par
"You'll have to say so yourself," said Jeff, brushing at himself without much effect. "I've got mud all over me, and you've managed to make me good and wet, too."\par
"You'll dry," said Norby. "The mud will dry, too, and then you can shake it off."\par
"How about you?" said Jeff. "Are you waterlogged? You won't turn rusty, will you?"\par
"Nothing damages me," said Norby. "Stainless steel outside; and better than that inside." He carefully untwined a water-lily frond from around his middle and dropped it in the pond with a finicky gesture.\par
Norby put out his illumination, but it was getting light enough for Jeff to be able to see him even in its absence. "Now I know why a simple judo throw landed you on the dome of your hat," he said.\par
"You charged before I was ready," Norby said.\par
"I did no such thing. \i You \i0 charged," Jeff said.\par
"I mean you defended yourself before I was ready."\par
"No such thing, either. You just can't manage your own technology. You said so yourself when we were antigravving."\par
"It was hard, I admit, but I managed," Norby said. "Look at that landing."\par
"You managed imperfectly," Jeff insisted. "That landing nearly drove us through to China."\par
"Well, I try," said Norby in an aggrieved voice. "You couldn't get any other robot to do this for what you paid for me. Besides, it's not my fault. I was damaged in a spaceship crash, and then Mac fixed me so that I would be undamageable, you see. He used salvaged equipment for that and-"\par
"What salvaged equipment?" demanded Jeff.\par
"Oh, well, if you're going to disbelieve everything I tell you, I've got nothing more to say."\par
\i "What \i0 salvaged equipment? Darn it, you've got to answer my questions \i sometimes. \i0 You're a robot, aren't you?"\par
"Yes, I'm a robot, so why don't you understand I've got to tell the truth?"\par
Jeff took a deep breath. "You're right. If I sounded incre\-dulous, I apologize. What salvaged equipment, Norby?"\par
"Salvaged equipment from an old spaceship we found on an asteroid."\par
"That's impossible-I believe you, Norby, I believe you. I know you wouldn't lie, but that's impossible. Nobody's ever found a ship on an asteroid just lying around. Wrecks are always salvaged at once by Space Command. In this computerized age, Space Command always knows when a wreck takes place, and exactly where, too."\par
"Well, this one wasn't salvaged by Space Command. It was just lying there, and it was salvaged by \i us. \i0 And how can I tell you which asteroid it was? There are a hundred thousand of them. It was a small asteroid that looked exactly like all the other small asteroids."\par
"What happened when he repaired you?"\par
"He just kept chuckling all the time. He seemed very pleased with himself and kept saying, 'Oh boy, oh boy, wait till they see this.' He was a genius, you know. I asked him what it was all about, but he wouldn't tell me. He said he wanted me to be surprised. And then he died, and I never found out."\par
"Never found out what?"\par
"About the things I could do. Like antigrav. And how to do it. Sometimes I can't get things sorted out in time, and that's why you could throw me. And then I don't land right because I don't have enough time to make the judgments I need. Please don't tell anyone about this."\par
"Are you kidding? Of course not."\par
"The scientists would take me apart, or try to, in order to find out how I do the things I do, and I don't want them to ... to try to take me apart, I mean. I'd be glad to tell them if I only knew myself."\par
Jeff sat back, his arms wrapped around his muddy knees. He looked up at the sky, which was reddening now in the onrush of morning. "You know, I'll bet it was an \i alien \i0 space\-ship. It would be the first real proof that there is alien intel\-ligence out beyond our Solar System. In fact, Norby, if that were so, \i you \i0 would be the first real proof of that."\par
"But you won't tell. You promised." Norby's voice sounded panicky.\par
"Never! I won't tell-Friend." Jeff reached out and shook Norby's hand. "But we've got to get on with the solstice celebration."\par
"All right," said Norby, "but that might not be easy. It seems to me that there's a herd of elephants somewhere."\par
Footsteps were indeed approaching. Lots of them.\par
Jeff seized Norby and scuttled behind a bush. Down the path between the trees came a group of people. Each person was holding binoculars.\par
"Bird-watchers," whispered Jeff.\par
"What are those?" Norby asked. "A new species of human being? I haven't seen anything like that before."\par
"That's because you spent too much time in space with McGillicuddy watching asteroids. Human beings like to ob\-serve the activities of other animals. These people watch birds, not asteroids."\par
"You mean they pry into the privacy of birds?"\par
"Birds don't care."\par
"But don't these human beings have anything better to do?"\par
"Watching birds is a good action. Would you rather they stood about and littered?"\par
"Birds litter. They-"\par
"Shut up, Norby."\par
The leading human, an elderly lady in tweeds, stopped be\-side the fishpond. "Here," she said, "is a good place to watch for owls. We've had them in Central Park for the last century. Before that, they would stop here occasionally, but wouldn't stay. There were always enough rats and mice for them to eat, but either the air was too polluted or the city was too noisy. Either way, they would decide that the price of a good meal was too high. Now they seem to like Manhattan, as all of us good Manhattan patriots do. At least the little screech owls do. I've been told they nest in the trees around here, and since it is not yet sunrise, there's hope we may see an owl on the move."\par
"I don't want to see an owl on the move," said Norby.\par
"What's that?" said the tweedy woman sharply. "Who said that? If there's anyone here who doesn't want to see owls, why did you come?"\par
"I don't like owls. They're probably scary," said Norby.\par
"Only if you look like a rat," whispered Jeff, "and you don't-though I wouldn't put it past you to act like one. Now keep quiet!"\par
"There's something behind that bush," said a boy. "Right there!"\par
"Muggers!" screamed a girl, waving her binoculars. "They'll knock us down and take our binoculars!"\par
"I don't need your binoculars," said Norby. "I have tele\-scopic vision when I want it."\par
"Really?" said Jeff, fascinated. "That could be convenient."\par
"Maybe they're Ing terrorists," said a man, "and they're holding a secret conference here in the park."\par
The group of bird-watchers was suddenly very still.\par
Jeff held his breath, and even Norby was quiet for a change.\par
At that moment, a shape detached itself from a dark tree and swooped down over the heads of the bird-watchers.\par
"We're being attacked by the terrorists," yelled the same man who had mentioned them before.\par
The woman in tweeds stood transfixed, clasping her hands. She didn't seem the least bit frightened-only excited. "Look! Look! It's a great gray owl! A Canadian! It's rarely seen this far south! My first Central Park sighting!"\par
The other bird-watchers paid no attention. They were scram\-bling back up the path, clutching their binoculars. "Let's go back," one of them shouted. "What's the use of watching birds when terrorists are watching \i us."\i0\par
Jeff couldn't bear to ruin the bird-watching. He didn't par\-ticularly want to get involved, but he had no choice. He stood up, facing the bird-watching leader. "I'm not a terrorist, ma'am, or a mugger, either. I'm here to celebrate the summer solstice. A family tradition."\par
"Oh my," said the woman. "The owl is gone."\par
"I hope so," said Norby. "It was big enough to decide I was a mouse."\par
Jeff pushed Norby with his elbow. "I'd be ashamed to be afraid of a little bird."\par
"A little bird? Its wings were twelve feet across!"\par
"Quiet!" said Jeff, and Norby subsided, muttering.\par
"Perhaps you'll see it again, ma'am," Jeff said.\par
"I certainly hope so. Seeing it even once was the thrill of my life-but what is that behind the bush?"\par
"That's-uh-sort of my baby brother. He scares easily."\par
"I do not," said Norby. "I'm as brave as a spacer."\par
"As a what?" asked the woman.\par
"He said he's brave. He's not afraid of anything as long as he knows he can run away."\par
"I'm as brave as a lion," shouted Norby.\par
"He's never even seen a lion."\par
"I've seen lions in pictures," Norby said. "Mac had an old encyclopedia on his ship. I know how to be brave. I don't run from danger."\par
"Your baby brother talks quite well for someone so small," said the woman, edging toward the bush.\par
"He's a prodigy," Jeff said, blocking her off, "but he's very shy. You'll embarrass him very much if you come too close. Of course, he does talk a lot, but that's only because he has a big hat-mouth, I mean. Now I really have to start celebrating the solstice."\par
The woman said timidly, "I don't suppose I could watch?"\par
"No, you can't. You're supposed to be bird-watching, not me-watching," shouted Norby.\par
"He means it's just a private family ceremony," Jeff said apologetically. "It's not traditional for anyone to watch."\par
There came a shout from the woods. "Are you all right, Miss Higgins?"\par
The woman smiled. "See that. They were very afraid, but they came back to rescue me. That's very touching isn't it?" She raised her voice. "I'm perfectly all right, good friends. I will be right with you." Then, again to Jeff, "Would you like to join our group some other morning?"\par
"Oh, certainly," said Jeff, "but hadn't you better go back to them? They must be dying with worry for you."\par
"I'm sure they are. We meet every Wednesday morning and on special occasions. I'll send you a notice. What is your name and address?"\par
Jeff told her, and she wrote it down in a small black note\-book.\par
Off in the distance, the owl hooted.\par
"This way!" called Miss Higgins to her group. "We may get another glimpse of it."\par
She plunged back into the darkness of the wood, and Jeff could hear that she had found her group and was leading them off on another path. Finally the park seemed deserted again, except for the small sounds of animals and the predawn twit\-tering of birds.\par
"That was horrible!" Norby said.\par
"Not at all," Jeff said. "It was just a little delay, and a harmless one. Far worse things used to happen in good old Central Park."\par
"Muggers and terrorists?" Norby asked. "Tell me about them."\par
"They're violent people from long ago. Central Park is per\-fectly civilized today."\par
"Then why did you say you weren't supposed to go into the park at night?"\par
Jeff blushed. "Fargo worries about me too much. Sometimes he thinks I'm a little kid. Still, the park is civilized now. You'll see."\par
"I'd better see," said Norby. "I'm a very civilized object, and I prefer to avoid anything uncivilized."\par
