\fs22 "It's only a small lion," said Norby plaintively. "Just a cub."\par
"A cub, my foot!" said Jeff, who was clutching Norby and backing toward the kitchen door. "It's almost full-grown and you know it. Where did you get it?"\par
"In a sort of zoo," said Norby. "It jumped on me and came with me when I went into hyperspace to get home. It wasn't my fault. It \i followed \i0 me."\par
Admiral Yobo grunted and stood up. Slowly, majestically, he picked up the chair on which he had been sitting and held it in front of him, the legs pointing at the advancing lion. He moved around the table until he was standing in front of Jeff, shielding him.\par
The lion roared, and Yobo brandished the chair menacingly. The lion snarled and lifted one broad paw.\par
Norby's hat slammed down until his head had disappeared inside the barrel. His arms and legs sucked inward as well, so that only the metal barrel remained in view.\par
"Coward," muttered Jeff, but he might have been talking to himself. He was ashamed that he was not defending his own admiral as a space cadet should, instead of vice versa.\par
The lion's uplifted paw showed its claws as he hit out at the chair leg.\par
"Get back, you fatuous feline," shouted Yobo, stamping his foot as he pushed the chair forward.\par
"What zoo?" Jeff asked Norby as the lion began to alter\-nately growl and roar.\par
"Not a nice one," came the words through the hat. "Very bad."\par
"I can see that," said Jeff. "The lion looks underfed."\par
"Cadet!" roared Yobo, louder and deeper than the lion. "Stop practicing the fine art of conversation by making diagnostic comments. \i Do \i0 something. Get into the kitchen and send for help. My ancestors might have battled lions, but not while wearing dress uniforms. I don't plan to get down to hand-to-paw wrestling with this beast. It looks as though it might have fleas."\par
The lion sprang and Yobo met it with the chair and forced it back. It snarled again and the muscles in its haunches bunched as if it were about to spring again, possibly over the chair.\par
Jeff put Norby down and ran to the table. The lion, possibly surprised at the sudden movement, stopped snarling at the ad\-miral and turned its menacing yellow eyes on Jeff, who snatched up what was left of the roast chicken and threw it at the lion.\par
"A dubious accomplishment," said Yobo, as the lion re\-treated to a corner and began to devour the chicken, bones and all. "You've bought a little time, at the cost of feeding my dinner to that underfed, oversized cat. Now get to the phone and...."\par
