"Right," said Jeff with sudden satisfaction. "Zi told me the Jamyns weren't allowed to travel to other planets, and I pre\-sume people from other planets aren't allowed to travel to Jamya. She said we were the first visitors ever. So let's go somewhere else."\par
Norby said, "We got to Jamya before because we used hyperdrive and went past the barrier by going out of normal space. All we have to do is to use hyperdrive now."\par
"Wait," Jeff said. He knew Fargo and he knew Norby, and there wasn't much use trying to talk sense to either of them. The only thing to do was to place another problem before them and then, maybe, he could get some sleep. With his eyelids drooping on their own, what he needed very badly was a little unconsciousness. After that, he might be able to face Jamya. "Don't you think you ought to find out why the Mentors want that hassock?" he asked.\par
"Isn't the best way of finding that out simply to ask the Mentors?" Fargo asked.\par
"No," Jeff said earnestly. "They never thought about the hassock till Norby mentioned it. Maybe they don't know what's in it. And it's Norby who thinks he can open it if he can work out the meaning of all that stuff around the sides."\par
"You're right. Sensible boy! Norby, make a note-your young owner has the makings of a brilliant adult."\par
"Yes, Fargo," Norby said, "I have always suspected that. It isn't easy to decipher the designs on the hassock, though."\par
Jeff heaved a sigh of relief. "I'm sure it isn't, so just take your time Norby, and don't hurry it. And while you're working I'll catch up on some much-needed sleep. Fargo, \i please, \i0 don't do \i anything \i0 while I'm sleeping!"\par
Fargo yawned. "I won't," he said. "I could use a little nap myself." He leaned back in his chair, pushed his pilot's cap over his eyes and was, in fact, asleep almost before Jeff was.\par
\par
Eight hours later Fargo and Jeff were eating breakfast while Norby was trying to explain that the Others' code was extremely difficult.\par
"But why?" asked Jeff. "You understand the Jamyn lan\-guage, so why can't you read their writing?"\par
"Because it's not just writing. It's \i code!" \i0 said Norby, a bit shrilly. "And it may not be Jamyn. This is probably a code used by the Others-whoever they are-and it may not be coded from the Jamyn language. Anyway, I've got part of it. The first half says 'All-purpose.' At least, I think it does."\par
"All-purpose what?" asked Jeff.\par
"I don't know. I can't make out the second half."\par
Fargo grinned and took the last synthobiscuit. "All-purpose flour? All-purpose weapon?"\par
"It probably just means all-purpose cushion," said Jeff, dis\-couraged. "That's what the hassock was used as. The dragons used it to rest their tails on. It was apparently very good for that. And I suppose you're no nearer to opening it now than you were at the start."\par
"No." The little robot's eyelids lowered halfway, and Jeff almost expected a teardrop of oil to come out.\par
"Any hints?" asked Fargo. "I mean, as far as opening it is concerned."\par
"Well, besides the words calling the hassock an all-purpose something, there are numbers. They come in batches in an odd pattern."\par
"Show me," said Fargo.\par
He and Norby huddled over the print-out from the computer, which represented Norby's attempts to solve the riddle of the hassock.\par
As for Jeff, he stared at the viewscreen while the other two muttered to each other. The planet, Jamya, seemed to swing in the black ocean of space, wreathed with clouds. He thought he could see blue ocean and green-brown landmasses beneath the clouds-or was it just one large landmass? Were the drag\-ons the only intelligent creatures on Jamya? Jeff thought they probably were, because Zi had not mentioned any other civi\-lized creatures besides the Mentors.\par
And what of the Mentors? Why did they want the hassock? And what task had they wanted Jeff to perform? They had never gotten around to describing that. What could one boy do that the Mentors and their powerful computer could not?\par
Jeff shook his head. He couldn't figure it out. He hoped Norby was doing better with the hassock.\par
Meanwhile Fargo said, "If that part of the code stands for numbers, it may be a double code with the numbers standing for words."\par
"If so, Fargo, it's too much for me," Norby said. "I'm just a small stupid robot and you mustn't expect too much of me."\par
Jeff realized that things were pretty bad for Norby to whine along those lines.\par
"Let up for a while, Fargo. Why don't we just sit and sing for a while until our brains clear."\par
There was a long pause while Fargo simply stared at his younger brother. Then he pounded his right fist into his left palm. "My brother is a genius."\par
"Why? What did I do?"\par
Fargo was too busy laughing to answer, so Norby answered for him.\par
"I think," he said, "that Fargo's decided that the numbers on the hassock stand for musical notes. I think he's right. As soon as you mentioned music, Jeff, my brain told me it was the solution. I'm surprised Fargo saw it, too. You both have your moments-for human beings."\par
It took another hour, but, with the help of Norby and the \i Hopeful's \i0 computer, Fargo decided he had the song.\par
"Shall I sing it?"\par
"Yes!" said Norby.\par
"No!" said Jeff. "Let me get a stun gun first, in case the hassock turns out to be a lethal robot machine of the Others."\par
"We don't have any stun guns," Fargo said cheerfully. "You know my motto 'clever words are all you need.'"\par
"Albany uses karate," said Jeff.\par
"Well," said Fargo, shrugging, "beautiful women have their ways. If there's a nasty little machine inside that hassock, we'll make it Norby's responsibility to deal with it."\par
"Why me?" asked Norby.\par
"Because you have your moments-for a robot."\par
Jeff laughed. "Well, then, go ahead, Fargo. Sing."\par
Fargo sang the coded notes. After the last note rang out, they watched the hassock. Nothing happened.\par
"Wrong rhythm, do you suppose?" Fargo asked.\par
"I think it should be in a minor key," said Norby, "now that I come to think of it."\par
"If you didn't have your thought processes mixed up," said Jeff, "you'd come to think of it beforehand instead of after\-ward."\par
"Better afterward than not at all," said Norby loftily. "My alien machinery has been a big help to you. How far would you have gotten on this hassock without me?"\par
"True enough," said Jeff.\par
Fargo sang again, a sad song this time, slow and melancholy, and Jeff wondered what the hassock might contain that had to be released in this sorrowful fashion.\par
The song ended. The three in the control room, and the ship's computer, too, were all silent. Outside, the planet Jamya was also silent.\par
But something began to happen. The hassock cover seemed to be getting thinner, lighter-and suddenly it cracked in two, the halves falling apart like a neatly struck eggshell.\par
"By all the satellites of Jupiter," said Fargo, "what is \i that?"\i0\par
It was green and fuzzy-or maybe they were fuzzy scales, or scales so small and neat as to look like fuzz. Whatever it was, it looked like another dragon, all curled up with its head hidden.\par
The creature uncurled, shook itself, and the scales became much fuzzier. It was a small animal about the size of a cat, with a round head and tiny pointed ears, a thin gold collar, and an odd snout with fangs.\par
Fargo backed away. "Norby, do you think we ought to be protected from that fanged thing?"\par
Norby did nothing but stare at the creature.\par
"Is it familiar to you, Norby?" Jeff asked in Jamyn, hoping the creature would understand.\par
Its small ears pricked up, but the animal only yawned. It shook itself once more, stretched, and began to circumnavigate the control room-sniffing at everything and waving its long, very fuzzy tail.\par
"When cats wave their tails, it means they're angry," said Fargo.\par
"But when dogs do, they're happy," said Jeff. "If this is like the dragons, it ought to be able to understand when we speak Jamyn."\par
"As a matter of fact," said Norby, "it's a 'she,' and she doesn't talk. She's not very bright, you see, but she's not dangerous, either. I remember now."\par
"Why was she hidden away like that in the hassock?"\par
"I can't quite figure that out."\par
"How do you know it's a 'she'?" asked Fargo.\par
"They all are. Like the dragons. Only this type lays eggs."\par
The fuzzy green creature got as far as Jeff and stood on her hind legs to sniff him. He put out his hand and let her sniff that, too. She didn't bite, but bumped her head under his palm as if she wanted him to stroke her. Automatically, he did so, thinking that she acted just like a cat, even if she didn't feel like one. She felt both soft and bristly, a combination that Jeff couldn't find words to describe.\par
"I always wanted a cat," he said.\par
Under his hand, the creature began to change-the snout receding, the ears and tail lengthening, the fangs disappearing. "Meow!" it said softly.\par
"It \i is \i0 a cat," said Fargo. "Come here, kitty!"\par
The creature ran to Fargo.\par
"Nice kitty," he said as he stroked her, "Can you be a dog?"\par
It was even more amazing. She changed her body contours until she looked very much like a dog. "Woof!" she said.\par
"Now I remember," said Norby. "That's an All-Purpose Pet."\par
Jeff said, "The Others may not be so bad after all. I like their taste in pets."\par
"Let's hope she continues to like \i us," \i0 said Fargo, cuddling the All-Purpose Pet, who now resembled a very green beagle (Fargo had always been partial to beagles). She licked his ear and purred.\par
"Beagles aren't supposed to purr," said Jeff, somewhat an\-noyed. He couldn't understand why females seemed to like Fargo best. He was glad he had Norby, who wasn't at all cuddly, but was \i his \i0 robot and never showed any signs of wanting to like anyone else instead.\par
Fargo said, "Let her purr. I'm going to name her Oola!"\par
"Why Oola?" Jeff asked.\par
"Because it seems to fit her," Fargo said.\par
The All-Purpose Pet pricked up her ears, now long and drooping, and whined a little.\par
Fargo chucked her under the chin and said, "How about that? Do you like your name-Oola?"\par
She patted Fargo's face with her paw-more like a cat than a dog-and grinned, with her tongue hanging out.\par
"See," said Fargo. "It's her name. She admits it."\par
"You've got a pet that's half beagle and half Cheshire cat," said Jeff, "and she'll probably change to fit everyone's mental wish and you'll never know \i what \i0 you've got." He still felt a bit jealous. "I wonder where the Others got her?"\par
"Made her, probably," said Norby. "Some day on our travels we'll find the animals the Others took genes from to do the biosynthesis of this one. And don't ask me how I know this!"\par
"We won't," said Jeff, while Fargo continued to play with Oola. "But I do think, Norby, it's time for you to tell us why you brought us back to Jamya-before we go down there to risk life and limb."\par
There was a long silence. Finally Norby spoke very softly.\par
"Because I think it's home," he said. "More and more, I think it's home-\i my \i0 home, and I don't want to be afraid of home."\par
