\pard\keepn\nowidctlpar\s5\b\fs28 More Time And Trouble\par
\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284\b0\fs19\par
\fs22 A cold apprehension gripped Jeff. It had nothing to do with the Mentors. Was Norby going to begin to feel as though he were a Jamyn? Wasn't part of him Terran? Was he going to choose between his two parts and turn his back on Jeff?\par
"Hey, Norby," Jeff said, sounding as jovial as he could, to conceal his feelings. "Don't get upset. We'll help you discover all about Jamya and you'll find there's nothing to fear."\par
The trouble was, Jeff thought inwardly, that he had been making entirely too many caustic remarks about Norby's being mixed up.\par
"The Mentors are after you, Jeff," Norby said. "I don't know why they think they can use you, but I don't think you ought to take the chance. I'd better go down to the planet without you. I can always escape them by moving into hyper-space."\par
"Oh, no," Jeff said. "You're not getting away from me-I mean, I can't let you take any chances without me. You and I are a team, an inseparable team, now and always. Right, Norby?"\par
"If I may interrupt this dialog," said Fargo with a grin on his face, "I'd like to point out that I am the senior member of this expedition, so I have to be consulted when decisions are made. I say that we're \i all \i0 going. Together. You don't think, do you, that I'm going to sit here and spend my time wondering what's happening to my little brother and his robot?"\par
"Well," said Norby, "that would be three of us against the villains-providing I don't have to spend all my time rescuing you two."\par
"There'll be some spare time for you to hide behind us, Norby," said Fargo, stroking Oola, who was lying in his lap.\par
"Leave Norby alone, Fargo," Jeff said. "He never hides behind anybody."\par
"I don't?" Norby said in a surprised tone.\par
"Besides," Jeff hurried on, "I have an idea. Those Mentors down there seemed very dangerous and not likely to listen to reason. But they are all very old and lots of them are dead and maybe they've deteriorated with time. After all, they were put on Jamya by the Others to teach the Jamyn how to be civilized. Why don't we go backward in time to when Jamya was first found by the Others and before they put up the force barrier? Maybe we'll speak to the young Mentors when they were healthy and reasonable."\par
"Hmm," murmured Fargo, "and then we'd know what the Others were like. Not a bad idea."\par
"I don't like it," Norby said. "The Others were probably more dangerous than the Mentors."\par
"Do you remember that they were?" Jeff asked.\par
"Well, no. I feel as though no part of me came into existence until long after the Others left, so I guess I wouldn't know anything about them."\par
"Are you telling us," Fargo asked, "that some of your parts are the creation of the Mentors?"\par
"That could be," Norby said. "I don't really know. I can't even remember what I used to be. Maybe I wasn't really a robot. Maybe I was a computer on that spaceship that McGillicuddy found. Anyway, I'm scared of the Others."\par
"Then we won't go back that far in time," Jeff said. "Do you think you can take us back the right amount if all of us concentrate on young Mentors?"\par
"Well," said Norby, "Fargo can't help, but you and I can join telepathically, and I'll try to link myself with the \i Hopeful, \i0 too, and we'll go back to soon after the Mentors arrived-I hope."\par
"Good! I'm sure the young Mentors will be reasonable," said Jeff. "Come here, Norby. Sit at the ship's computer, and I'll hold your hand."\par
A little wire pushed out of Norby's hat and inserted itself into the ship's computer. His hand grabbed Jeff's and held tight.\par
"Okay?" Norby asked.\par
"I'm not afraid," said Jeff. "In fact, I'm completely con\-fident in you, Norby. If we could get back from the Ice Age smack into the \i Hopeful's \i0 control room, we ought to be able to move the \i Hopeful \i0 back into time with pinpoint accuracy."\par
Jeff closed his eyes so he could concentrate better-also to shut out the doubting expression on his brother's face. So what if Norby got things wrong now and then? Think of all the things he got right! Norby kept saying that, and he was right, too!\par
Now ... concentrate on Jamya... move back... back... to a much earlier time.... think of Mentors, with shiny metal, moving easily, resonant, pleasant voices....\par
"Jeff!" Fargo's voice was urgent. "Norby! The two of you- come out of it!"\par
"What... what...." Jeff came to, Wearily. "What's wrong?"\par
"I'm not sure. You two have been still and silent for half an hour. You didn't tell me how this works, either of you. Does it take you that long to do it?"\par
"I don't know. Didn't anything happen?"\par
"Nothing at all. I had a momentary sensation of dizziness at the start, but it passed, and here we still are and there Jamya still is."\par
Norby was quite conscious, too, for he made a snorting noise and pulled his wire out of the computer. "Of course, we're still here and Jamya is still there, but the position of its sun is different. It's now spring in the continent where the dragons live-a long ago spring."\par
"You mean we've moved back in time?"\par
"Of course!"\par
"In that case," said Fargo. "Get out of my chair, little robot, and let me take us down to this planet of yours."\par
He put Oola on the control room floor, where she sat plac\-idly, and licked herself like a cat while still looking like a beagle.\par
Down they went, skimming across the Jamyn continent.\par
Jeff said, "Can you find Zi's castle, Norby? You did that two times before without trouble."\par
"In \i our \i0 time, Jeff. The castle doesn't exist at this time in the past."\par
"I mean....Locate the place where the castle will some day exist?"\par
"I get no feel for it," said Norby, sounding worried.\par
The \i Hopeful \i0 skimmed low over the planetary ocean and headed back over the continent again.\par
"Trees. Lots of trees," Fargo said. "Those sea creatures that looked up at us might be interesting."\par
"No," said Norby sharply. "The Mentors chose land crea\-tures to civilize. Maybe we went back too far. Maybe there's no animal life on land at all."\par
"Not likely," Fargo said, "when it's so richly forested and vegetated. See, there's a group of animals below in the grass\-land." He sent the \i Hopeful \i0 downward in a sharply banked curve for a closer view. "They look something like bipedal dinosaurs, but I don't see any sign of wings."\par
"That's odd," said Jeff. "They don't even have them furled. I think they don't have any wings."\par
The \i Hopeful \i0 came in for a quiet landing and rested upon the grass at some distance from the herd. Fargo moved to open the airlock.\par
"Hey," said the ever cautious Jeff, "aren't you going to analyze the .air outside?"\par
Fargo paused. "You've been here, haven't you? And you breathed. And you're alive."\par
"That was at a different time. Why don't you ask the com\-puter?"\par
"Oh, well." Fargo looked pained. "What's the air like?"\par
The computer said, "Breathable. There are plant seeds and spores to which allergies might exist, but I can't test for that without more information."\par
"We'll chance it," Fargo said, as he picked up Oola.\par
They moved out on the grass, which was waving in the wind. It was rather cool, but Jeff remembered the glacier and decided that he could get along easily with \i this \i0 kind of coolness.\par
Jeff said, "I'll just step over there and speak to the dragons. I can speak Jamyn, you know."\par
"Look out!" yelled Norby, tugging at Jeff's pant legs.\par
The dragons were approaching \i en masse, \i0 and at a run. They were also speaking, but not in Jamyn. Their language, if it could be called that, consisted entirely of loud roars, screeches, and hisses, punctuated by little puffs of smoke from their nos\-trils.\par
"Jeff, old boy," said Fargo, trying to control Oola, who was snarling and barking alternately. "These are \i not \i0 friends of yours. It's my opinion we had better get back into the ship at once."\par
Without arguing the matter, they did so, shutting the airlock behind them.\par
"I thought you told me that the dragons were smaller than human beings," Fargo said.\par
These were as big as the \i Hopeful. \i0 In the viewscreen, they could see the dragons swarming over the ship, trying to find a place to bite. Their fangs sounded like jackhammers upon the hull.\par
"Fargo," Jeff said, "I don't think their teeth are made of ivory. They look shiny, as if they were made of metal, or of diamonds."\par
"You're right, Jeff, and they may damage us." He moved to the controls. "We'll have to get away."\par
"They aren't speaking Jamyn," said Norby unnecessarily. "I don't think they've ever been civilized."\par
Fargo moved the \i Hopeful \i0 slowly upward on antigrav so that the dragons clutching at the hull gradually peeled off. The huge animals were now spouting flames in their frustration. Fargo seemed fascinated.\par
"From a whiff I got outside," he said, "I think they make their flames by splitting hydrogen sulfide...."\par
"The computer says the hull is heating under those flames," said Norby. "We should get back into orbit."\par
Again there was no attempt to argue the matter, and the ship rose precipitously. When it was safely in orbit, the three had another conclave, while Oola chased her tail round and round in the control room.\par
"My feeling is," Fargo said, "that we \i did \i0 get back to a time before the Others, even before the Mentors created a civilization on this planet. We went backward in time too far."\par
"I think that's my fault," Jeff said. "Not Norby's. He did very well. It's just that when Norby and I were linked and trying to move backward in time, I felt some kind of fear, and perhaps that threw us off."\par
"You weren't feeling \i my \i0 fear," said Norby, sounding out\-raged. "I was certainly not afraid."\par
"No, no," said Jeff. "You don't understand. You see, I was thinking of the Mentors very hard. And I felt something about them that I must have felt when I was in their scanning room, but didn't realize I'd felt because I was too full of my own fears. Do you understand what I mean?" He looked at Fargo helplessly.\par
Fargo said, "Sure, but what was it you felt without knowing you felt it?"\par
"It was the \i Mentor \i0 who was afraid. I was feeling \i its \i0 fear when we were trying to move in time."\par
"Was the Mentor afraid of you, do you suppose?"\par
"No."\par
"Of the Others?" Norby asked.\par
"I don't think so," said Jeff. "The Mentor was awfully afraid, though, and he \i needed \i0 me. I don't know what for, but it had something to do with his fear."\par
"If he is afraid of something and needs your help," Fargo said, "it doesn't seem to me he can afford to do us any harm."\par
Sounding doubtful, Jeff asked, "Should we go forward, then, and see if we can find the young Mentors?"\par
"Can we?" said Fargo with a grin. "It's up to you two."\par
"Let's try again, Jeff," Norby said. "Maybe there's nothing to fear. Maybe it was only Mentors' fear that made you afraid."\par
Jeff almost said, 'You were more afraid than I was,' but he pressed his lips together and didn't say it. Instead, he held out his hand. "Sure," he said, "let's try again."\par
Half an hour later they gave up.\par
"No dizziness, no nothing," said Fargo. "I guess we're still in the same time."\par
"Well," said Norby, "it seems to be very different to go into a time I've already existed in. It's easier to move to a time earlier or later than when I've been there. Do you know what I mean? I tried to push us all forward until we were well past where the Mentors showed up, but I couldn't seem to do it."\par
"In that case," said Jeff, with a sinking feeling, "that would mean that you, or parts of you, were present on Jamya sometime after the Mentors appeared, just as you thought you might be. I guess you're really Jamyn."\par
"I suppose so," said Norby. "It's exciting, isn't it?"\par
Jeff didn't think so. But all he said was, "Can you slide forward only a little into the future, before the time when you were constructed?"\par
"I can try."\par
"I can see where it's difficult to move to a time where you've already existed," Fargo said, "because one of the big paradoxes of time-travel involves the possibility of meeting yourself. Still, why don't we go really far into the future and find out what happened to us in the Jamyn historical records of the future, so that we'll know what to do to fix everything up? That would be exciting!"\par
"That sounds like another paradox to me," Jeff said, sound\-ing unhappy. "I don't think we can do that. The future isn't all written out. Suppose we find out that we were killed when we went back to Jamya. Then we would be in despair and give up and that might be \i why \i0 we were killed."\par
"I don't understand that," said Norby, "but I don't want to be killed."\par
"Don't worry, little robot," Fargo said, "we won't let that happen, but I see Jeff's point. All right, Norby, just move us up into the nearest part of the future you can manage, shortly after the Mentors begin to work."\par
Jeff and Norby tried again. This time Jeff visualized a young Mentor and tried to feel full of confidence. He was distracted because Oola suddenly began to howl like a lost hound.\par
"Hush, hush, my beauty," said Fargo, stroking her long ears as she sat quivering, pressed against his leg. She stopped howl\-ing, but she whimpered instead.\par
Jeff was about to say, "Let's try it again, Norby," when Fargo cried out without any trace of his usual humor. "Wait! She's gone. Oola's gone."\fs24\par
