\fs22 "Hello," said Zargl. "You're back. You shouldn't be."\par
Jeff waved at her as he left the \i Hopeful, \i0 followed by Norby and Fargo. Then he waved at Zi, who was coming out of her home rather hurriedly at the sight of the ship.\par
"This is my sibling, Fargo," he said to mother and daughter dragon, pronouncing the name carefully. He hesitated before choosing the Jamyn word to describe Fargo's relationship to him. There was no Jamyn word for "brother," of course.\par
Jeff then asked, with a fine air of casualness, "How long have we been gone?"\par
"Fourteen day/nights," said Zargl. "Ever since you left, the Jamyns have been arguing about what to do if you returned. The Mentors sent word that you are to be captured and taken to the castle if we ever see you again. Isn't that exciting? Of course, they didn't expect you to come with a ship and rein\-forcements."\par
"Which probably makes it even more exciting," muttered Fargo, as Norby translated softly for him. "Maybe things won't be so tame at that. Ask this Pseudoreptile to bite me so I'll be able to understand her language."\par
"Good idea," said Jeff. "Then if things don't live up to your notions of danger and adventure, you'll at least be able to tell Albany that you were bitten by a dragon. And you, Norby, you can tell her how you missed by a couple of weeks again."\par
Norby said haughtily, "Can you do better, Jeff?"\par
Jeff, still mindful of his manners, said, "No, I can't. True is true. Zargl, would you bite my sibling, just a little bit. Just a tiny little bit."\par
Zargl said, "Certainly." She came shyly up to Fargo, and nuzzled his arm. "Your sibling is very attractive," she said to Jeff.\par
"There you are," said Jeff. "The girls always fall for him."\par
Fargo smiled. "It's to be expected. No one can resist my devil-may-care attitude and my incredible charm."\par
"It's the way he shows his little teeth," she said, showing her own much larger ones. Then she nipped a bit of flesh on Fargo's forearm between an opposing pair of her sharp teeth.\par
Fargo said, "Ouch," and frowned at the tiny droplet of blood that seeped from each of two delicate puncture marks.\par
"There you are," said Jeff. "The knowledge is transmitted by the blood somehow. The bite is so neatly done, it won't even bruise. In a few minutes, you'll be able to catch the Jamyn words telepathically, and not long after that you will understand them spoken aloud, and be able to speak them yourself."\par
Fargo waved his arm. "I wish they could teach differential equations that way."\par
Zi, who had been looking at the \i Hopeful \i0 very carefully, now pointed her right front claw at it and said, "What's that?"\par
"That's our small scoutship," Jeff explained. "It's ours free and clear; in fact, it was all we had left when the family business failed a few years ago...."\par
"Look at that!" said Fargo, with sudden energy. "Jeff, do you see what I see?"\par
Jeff turned to look at the \i Hopeful \i0 and there in the open airlock was a green creature peering up at the castle, and pant\-ing.\par
"Oola!" cried out Jeff in astonishment. "I'll bet she auto\-matically joined us when we went forward in time past the point when we opened the hassock."\par
"She seems to know the castle," Fargo said. \i "Look \i0 at her reacting to it."\par
Zi said, "I have never seen a creature like that before. How can she know the castle if I have never seen her?"\par
"Oola was inside your hassock," said Jeff, "the one you let us have. She was bioengineered by a particular Mentor named First."\par
"First?" Zi scratched her tail. "He is an important part of our legends. The great Mentor named First organized the con\-struction of the buildings on Jamyn, and carried out the in\-structions of the Others for the civilizing of the Jamyn and, as you see, did a very good job of it. All Jamyn are in awe of First and feel great respect for him."\par
"And where is First, now?"\par
"No one knows. Perhaps he is still at the castle. Perhaps he was the one that spoke to you on my computer screen."\par
"That can't be," said Jeff. "The Mentor who spoke to me, and who saw me in the castle, was malevolent."\par
A bell chimed in the dragons' house. "Excuse me," said Zi. "Zargl, come with me and begin the preparations of a meal for our guests, while I find out what the Grand Dragonship wants." In a lower-pitched version of her voice, she said to Jeff and Norby "It is a great honor for her to call upon a mere Con\-gressperson such as myself." She seemed to breathe quickly at the thought of it.\par
Left to themselves for a moment, Jeff said in Terran Basic, "Fargo, things seem no different here than when we left. Zi remembers our previous visit just as we do. Doesn't that mean that our visit to the past of Jamya didn't change anything?"\par
"Let's hope so," Fargo said.\par
Norby, however, teetered nervously on his partly extended legs. "I can tell, Jeff, I can tell. I can sense that nothing important has changed. Mentor First must really have had his memories of us wiped out. And that means that the Mentors in the castle right now are still crazy and mean."\par
"Good," said Fargo. "Maybe that will mean a chance for us to be battling real nasties."\par
Zi came out of her house carrying a little table, and Zargl followed with dishes of food. "You'll have to sit on the lawn," she said. "Please accept my apologies for that, but I have no furniture in my home that will fit your peculiar bodies-no offense intended. Even my hassock, my tail rest, is gone, for you have changed it into an unknown green animal. Still, it's such a lovely day, I thought you might be willing to have a picnic before the Grand Dragonship arrives."\par
"A picnic would be very welcome," said Jeff. "And I'm looking forward to meeting such an exalted person."\par
"And she's my great-aunt, too," said Zargl, holding up her foreclaws and making them quiver. "Isn't she, Mother?"\par
"She certainly is, my dear child, and my own aunt."\par
\par
Half an hour later, they were all, including Oola, finishing the meal. Oola kept looking up at the castle and twitching her tail when Norby suddenly shot up on antigrav, his foot catching Jeff's ear on the way.\par
"What are you doing?" asked Jeff, rubbing his ear hard.\par
"I want to hurry back to the \i Hopeful," \i0 said Norby. "I suggest you two bring Oola and join me. Look what's coming."\par
From over the trees at the left of the castle, came a strange airborne procession. Majestically, a retinue of Jamyn flew to\-ward Zi's home, and from their jeweled claws hung a glittering hammock that supported a dragon considerably larger than Zi.\par
"It's my aunt," cried Zi, clacking her teeth in excitement and respect. "Please do not leave. I so want you to meet her."\par
The hammock came overhead and was let down in front of them, dragons hovering about with a great swirl of wings to insure that it landed safely.\par
"Make way for her Grand Dragonship," shouted all the dragons in a medley of squawks that was totally unmusical.\par
When the hammock was flat on the lawn, the Grand Dragon stepped off it. She unfurled her wings, each leathery portion brightly painted in contrasting colors, and shook them. A diamondlike jewel adorned each point of the projections that went down her back to the tip of her gilded tail.\par
"So, my niece," she said, holding herself high with her wings akimbo to make the colors show dramatically, "you make friends with the enemy when I instructed you not to!"\par
"I'm sorry, Aunt-Your Dragonship-but I do like these humans and their little robot. And Zargl and I had already made friends with them weeks ago, so it was already too late when your instructions came. And see, they have discovered this green creature that was inside my tail rest-which they call by the interesting nonsense word, 'hassock.'"\par
"You don't understand," said Her Dragonship. "This green creature, as you call it, is the Mentors' Pet. They have watched the situation through monitors and they have sent me to correct the theft. Otherwise \i we \i0 will be punished."\par
"Correct the \i theft?" \i0 asked Fargo. "What do you mean by that? The hassock was given us by your niece freely."\par
"Nevertheless," said the Grand Dragon, "you two strangers and your ugly robot and this pet will be brought to the Mentors."\par
Norby said to Jeff in a furious whisper, "Are you just going to stand there and let her call me ugly?"\par
Oola whined and became more like a beagle than ever.\par
Fargo said, "This pet is my pet. It belongs to me now."\par
"No, she doesn't," screamed the Grand Dragon, stamping her foot, which was large and had wicked claws on it. "My guards will prove that by overpowering you...."\par
"That would not be sporting, Your Dragonship," said Fargo.\par
He paused and bent down to Norby. "Have I got the right word? Jamyn is not an easy language to learn in a great hurry."\par
"Say it isn't \i fair," \i0 Norby said in Jamyn. "Dragons don't play sports the way you do, but they are fair."\par
"Surely, Your Dragonship, you have some more civilized way of settling a dispute than brainless force?" Fargo smiled his most charming smile.\par
The dragon guards began to move toward him, but the Grand Dragon gestured them back. "This stranger appeals to our civ\-ilized nature," she said, "and no one can appeal to that in vain. It would be an insult to the Mentors otherwise."\par
She smiled, too, her pointed teeth and front fangs showing to full advantage. She adjusted her jeweled gold collar and stepped forward until she was only a few centimeters from Fargo. She was a little taller than he was, and, counting the tail, considerably bigger.\par
"There! It will be I alone against two of you and a robot. It is three to one in your favor so it is you who will be unci\-vilized, yet I will personally bring all of you to the Mentors."\par
"Is that indeed so?" said Fargo, as he thrust out his chin.\par
"Fargo!" said Jeff, reverting to Terran Basic, "Let's just go with her...."\par
"Never!" said Fargo, pushing up his sleeves.\par
"Listen, you're not going to try to punch her, are you?" asked Jeff. "Her fangs will tear into your knuckles."\par
"Fist fighting is crude," Fargo said, adjusting his stance. "I'm going to see if I can use any of the defensive arts that Albany has taught me. I wouldn't mind having a sword or rapier, though. Cold steel against hot fang, eh?"\par
"This isn't funny!" said Jeff."You can't win!"\par
Norby was ascending and descending on his telescopic legs, forcing his way between Jeff and Fargo and shouting, "Listen to me, you human idiots! The Jamyn respect tradition and authority and they never use force among themselves!"\par
"Well?" asked Fargo, "Are you trying to spoil the fun?"\par
"Of course. Your kind of fun is no fun. But there is some\-thing else...." He rose on antigrav and whispered in Fargo's ear.\par
Fargo nodded, but did not change his position, "En garde, sir, I mean, madam, Your Dragonship." He moved into the ready-to-attack position.\par
The Grand Dragon snorted and little puffs of smoke came out of her nostrils. "There, you see! You have made me revert to the primitivism of my ancestors; you have forced me to be angry enough to breathe fire. You ought to be ashamed of yourself."\par
"It would not be fair for you to use fire," Fargo said.\par
"I do not intend to. I will cow you by the superior nature of my personality and take you all to the Mentors, who will imprison you."\par
The Grand Dragon and Fargo moved toward each other. They began circling, feinting, and reaching. Suddenly the Grand Dragon lunged and Fargo went head over heels. The Grand Dragon drew back in surprise. Clearly, she hadn't expected that to happen.\par
Fargo picked himself up with a groan. "She's quick."\par
Jeff watched the battle with sinking heart. Karate against slippery dragon scales was not working too well. Fargo man\-aged to trip the Grand Dragon, who seemed more surprised than ever when \i she \i0 went down, but once she got back, she retaliated immediately, saying, "If you are going to be aggres\-sive, so will I."\par
"The fight isn't fair, Your Highness-ship," said Fargo gravely. "Your arms are much longer than mine. May I have a short stick?"\par
"Certainly, since that will make all the more plain your uncivilized nature and force you to abase yourself to my higher culture."\par
"Norby," said Fargo, "go get the skewer in the galley. You know the one that you were curious about the other day. That ought to be about the right length."\par
Jeff's eyebrows shot up. The object Norby had been curious about had been an apple picker that Fargo had bought at a tool sale, a sticklike device with a collapsible grasper at one end for plucking apples too high to reach by hand. Fargo would buy anything that was a bargain, however useless. It was one of the reasons the family business had done so badly after the deaths of their parents.\par
The battle began again with Fargo wielding the apple picker against the Grand Dragon's sharp foreclaws (which, however, she wielded so carefully that Fargo had not yet been scratched).\par
They again circled and circled, reaching out, feinting; but the Grand Dragon was obviously getting angry over the fact that Fargo had not yet admitted her superiority and given in.\par
She was puffing smoke in spite of herself and growing angrier still at this demonstration of her animal nature. Fargo took advantage of the manner in which her anger was disrupting her concentration. As she lunged forward, he leaped to one side, caught her arm, pulled her forward, and down she went.\par
"Bravo!" said Jeff.\par
"Stupid human being," muttered Norby. "Showing off, when I have told him how to conclude this ridiculous exercise in a perfectly simple way...."\par
"I'm not sure I should fight a female," said Fargo, pushing back his hair, "but there are no males on this planet for me to fight."\par
He stopped talking because the Grand Dragon was up, fire spurting out of her nostrils.\par
"That's very animal," said Fargo, waggling his apple picker at the Grand Dragon's nose.\par
She stifled the flame, but as Fargo sprang forward, she unfurled her wings and elevated, then made a feint at him from the air.\par
"Unfair!" shouted Jeff.\par
"It certainly is," said Fargo, reaching up with the apple picker, activating the grasper at the end and seizing the golden collar which circled her scaly neck-just as such collars circled the necks of every other dragon they had seen. One twist, a pull, and the collar was off.\par
"Mine!" shouted Fargo, "spoils of war!" He put it around his own neck, where it hung loosely.\par
Jeff watched what followed in amazement. The Grand Dragon, instead of soaring majestically, began to flap her wings frantically. The enormous effort broke her fall, but did not prevent it. She landed on the lawn with a loud "plop" and in a most undignified posture.\par
Her guards gaped. Zi and Zargl hid their mouths with their claws. Norby tittered metallically.\par
"What happened?" asked Jeff.\par
"This is an antigrav device," said Fargo, touching the collar. "I've been thinking that the dragons must be too heavy to fly, especially with such comparatively small wings, and Norby confirmed that."\par
"That's right, come to think of it," said Jeff. "They didn't have wings at all in their prehistoric history. Remember?"\par
"I do. The Mentors must have added them as part of their bioengineering program for esthetic reasons and perhaps to add stability in antigrav flight." Fargo elevated. "It's done mentally. One thinks 'up' and there one is. A great device. Probably Norby has one incorporated into his own works."\par
"Of course, I do," said Norby shrilly. "I keep telling you all the time I'm Jamyn in origin-in part."\par
"Now," said Fargo, "I think I'll pay a visit to the castle under my own steam and not as anyone's prisoner."\par
The the Grand Dragon had recovered from the mixture of shame and physical confusion that had beset her, and now she struggled to her feet. Her guards rushed to her side as she screamed, "Get that stranger! Bring him down!"\par
"No," said Fargo, skimming over her head. "I think not. I won the fight fairly and you cannot try to upset the result without showing yourself to be most uncivilized. You just sit there and recover, Your Majesty, while I...."\par
"No you don't," said Jeff. "Not alone, you don't." He snatched up Norby under his left arm and scooped up Oola with his right. "We're \i all \i0 going. Up Norby-to the castle."\par
