\fs22 Oola whined, her ears lengthening. She slunk on her belly over to Fargo.\par
Stroking her ears, Fargo muttered, "Poor Oola. I guess she's torn between Mentor First and me. And poor me, because I guess if Mentor First lives, I'll end up minus a pet."\par
"He'd better live," said Jeff, "even if it means you being petless. and he'd better come back with Norby intact, because without Norby, how are we going to get home? The \i Hopeful \i0 will be forever stuck within the energy barrier around Jamya if we can't make use of Norby's mixed-up abilities."\par
"You're right. But let's be optimistic. \i When \i0 Norby gets back, we'll go out in search of the Others, if they still exist."\par
"Or, if they don't, we must at least find that wrecked ship of theirs that McGillicuddy stumbled on. No telling what in\-formation it might have on it."\par
"Either way," said Fargo, "whether it's the Others, or their ship, we'd better do the finding before anybody else in the Federation does."\par
"Absolutely," said Jeff. "We could use that knowledge as ransom for Norby. It's Norby I worry about. Right now, and after we get back home!"\par
The two waited with increasing impatience. Then Fargo said, "This doesn't seem to be an appropriate time for it, but I'm getting hungry. How about you?"\par
Jeff said, "I'm a growing boy, superannuated brother. I'm more or less always hungry."\par
"Too bad. Part of the problem of being organic rather than metal is that one has to refuel so much more often. Do you suppose Zi will feed us if we go down there?"\par
"Sure, she's a great hostess, but her aunt, the Grand Dragon, will try to chew us up."\par
"Let me try my charm," Fargo said, sauntering out with Oola in his arms.\par
