\pard\nowidctlpar\fi284 Charm or whatever, Jeff thought a while later, it certainly worked.\par
Fargo, collarless since he had restored her property to the Grand Dragon, had eaten and was now serenading Her Drag\-onship, who sat in royal splendor against the sunset light of Jamya. She reached out with one careful claw every now and then and ran it through Fargo's hair.\par
"These are such pleasant scales," she said. "Soft and fine. How did you come to get them?"\par
"I have noticed," said Fargo, "that they have grown softer and finer since I have had the good fortune to meet you, Your Dragonship."\par
At this, the Grand Dragon made a gargling sound that seemed to signify gratified pleasure. She was obviously infatuated with him.\par
With his melodic tenor, Fargo had no trouble acting the part of a troubadour, and was now well into a peculiar translation of "God Save the Queen" which seemed to delight the Grand Dragon.\par
Jeff lacked Fargo's ability to live in the passing moment, however. He did not enjoy either the food or the song, for he could think only of the absent Norby. Even Zargl, who sat next to him and made fearsome faces at him in an apparent design to make him laugh, failed to cheer him up.\par
As the sun sank below the trees, the Grand Dragon offered to fly Jeff and Fargo to her palace where they might spend the night. It seemed to the appalled Jeff that Fargo might actually accept the invitation, and he said, "I think we had better stay in the \i Hopeful, \i0 in case our small robot returns."\par
Fargo, looking guilty for a moment, agreed.\par
But Norby did not return. The night was very dark because Jamya had no satellite and seemed to be in a section of space rich in cosmic dust that dimmed most of the stars that might have been visible in the sky.\par
"Fargo," Jeff said, as he lay in the top bunk of their cabin. "I'm so worried I can't sleep."\par
Only snores answered him. Fargo could sleep through any\-thing.\par
Jeff stared gloomily at the darkness above with increasingly dire visions passing through his mind, when he heard Oola's paws plunk against the floor and pad down the corridor to the control room. Apparently, she had leaped down from Fargo's stomach, where she had been curled up when the lights were put out.\par
Jeff slid over the edge of his bunk, dropped quietly to the cabin floor, and followed her.\par
"What is it, girl?" he said, scratching her behind the ears. She must have changed into a cattish phase now, for her eyes shone in the dim lights from the control panels.\par
Crash! A falling object struck the Captain's chair, bounced to the floor, and rolled.\par
Jeff put on the room light. Out of the falling object, half a head popped up and large eyes peered from under a metal derby hat.\par
"Norby!" Jeff cried out in sheer joy. The pleasantest sight in the world, it seemed to him, was the little robot appearing out of nowhere, even if he failed to make a good landing. What other robot would be as clumsy as delightful, wonderful, mixed-up Norby?\par
Norby said, "Sorry, Jeff. I was so upset I forgot to turn on my antigrav when I reappeared from hyperspace. Didn't you get my telepathic message warning you I was trying to get back?"\par
"No, but I think Oola did."\par
"That's very annoying," said Norby. "We're going to have to work on your long-distance telepathy... but that's for later. Right now, you've got to wake up Fargo, and both of you had better help me take the \i Hopeful \i0 back to the Terran solar system. After we refueled in hyperspace, the Mentor First and I tuned into the Others' supply ship and found it on an asteroid, but so have the pirates. I came back here to get help."\par
"What about Mentor First?"\par
"He's holding off the pirates, and I don't know how long he can do that, so we'd better get to him \i fast\i0 ."\par
"Did I hear you say pirates?" asked Fargo from the doorway.\par
"I'll say it again. Pirates! Pirates!" yelled Norby. "Let's get going." He grabbed both brothers and all three ran to the com\-puter.\par
The \i Hopeful \i0 emerged in normal space next to the asteroid.\par
"Wow-from Jamya slam-bang through hyperspace to my own solar system! And right on target, Norby," said Fargo softly.\par
"Have you stopped being mixed up?" asked Jeff.\par
"I'm tuned to Mentor First. Getting us here was easy. Do you have any suggestions as to how to cope with those pirates who are trying to steal the Jamyn's supply ship? Look at the size of it!"\par
Following Norby's pointing finger, Jeff watched the view-screen intently while Fargo was whispering rapidly to the little robot.\par
Another ship, tiny by comparison, but larger than the \i Hope-fid \i0 was anchored to the small asteroid. Jeff could dimly see the huge outline of a strange wreck on the asteroid, partially hidden by its irregularities. On the asteroid, Mentor First was confronting three men in spacesuits who were holding weapons.\par
"But are they pirates?" asked Jeff, doubtful. "They could be Federation police."\par
"No chance," said Fargo. "Those are known pirates; I rec\-ognize their ship. They're renegades from the Inventors Union. Up and at 'em."\par
"With what?" asked Jeff. "The \i Hopeful \i0 doesn't carry weap\-ons."\par
"You're not up-to-date, little brother. Admiral Yobo insisted that once I became one of Space Command's secret agents, my ship would have to be armed. You and I will go out in suits and distract the pirates, and Norby will plug into system G6YY of the computer. The computer will tell you what to do, Norby."\par
Norby was plugging in. "Right, Fargo. Are you sure you also want me to notify...."\par
"Yes, those are my orders. I'm certain," said Fargo hastily, pulling Jeff to the airlock and throwing him a space suit from the three hanging there.\par
"Fortunately, we don't need antigrav in open space-or on an asteroid either," he added, readying the jet propulsion system of the suit. He and Jeff stepped into the airlock.\par
"I wish you'd tell me what we're planning to do," said Jeff in exasperation, over the suit's intercom.\par
"Just follow me."\par
Jeff followed, landing between the Mentor and the three pirates.\par
"Howdy," said Fargo. "How about cutting me in on the spoils, boys? If you've found anything, that is."\par
The pirates were clearly startled at the sudden and unex\-pected voice in their radio receivers. Apparently they had not been aware of a ship materializing silently out of hyperspace and into their vicinity.\par
One of the pirate guns turned on Fargo and Jeff, with the clumsiness that attended all movements in open space.\par
"Who are you?" demanded the pirate.\par
"Fargo Wells, descended from an ancestor who was tarred and feathered in North Dakota, American sector of the Terran Federation. My buddy here and I are interested in what you found. An old robot?"\par
"That robot's alive, mister," said the pirate leader, "and it's dangerous. If you want anything out of us besides destruction, you'd better get ready to help us. That thing is holding some gadget that repels our force guns and produces a nasty shock when you get near enough. If you two do something useful, maybe you'll get something in exchange."\par
Fargo said, "Sounds good, if you can really get something out of an old robot. Is \i that \i0 all you've got here?"\par
"The wreck of an alien ship, too, that the Inventors Union might pay a lot for."\par
"Why should they? Is there anything on the ship?"\par
"That's what we aim to find out, and we don't figure on delaying things with talk. Are you going to help us or do we poke holes in your suits and let out all that nice air?"\par
"As it happens," said Fargo, "we're attached to our air. My buddy here is a robotics expert, so let him approach that mon\-ster."\par
The three pirates touched fingers and conferred in sound, the waves being carried by the material of the suits. The first pirate, clearly the leader, switched back to radio.\par
"You have one chance," he said. "If you can handle the robot, fine! If not, say good-bye to each other real fast, because we're not going to wait for you to say your prayers."\par
Jeff used rocket microsurges to bring himself down to the asteroid surface and approached Mentor First in the slow, sway\-ing steps enforced by a nearly gravitationless world. He touched Mentor First and said, telepathically and in Jamyn,-Hold on, First, Fargo and I have come to....\par
